<h5>
Presentation 1: Strategies and Motivations in New Vegans and
Vegetarians: Findings from a Longitudinal Study
</h5>

<p>
Authors:
Jo Anderson &amp; Marina Milyavskaya
Speaker: Jo Anderson (Faunalytics, Carleton University)
</p>
<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>
Many campaigns encourage people to adopt and maintain vegan or
vegetarian (veg*n) diets, but long-term success seems rare, especially
among people with health goals (Faunalytics, 2014). Advocates need more
data about how to support long-term diet maintenance. Should we avoid
campaigning to the health-motivated, or just support them differently? To
answer these and other questions, we surveyed new veg*ns at seven time
points over the first 6 to 8 months of their diets. In this talk, we present
preliminary data about supports, strategies, and changes in motivation over
time. How often do initial motivations that are poor determinants of success
(including extrinsic health goals, per Self-Determination Theory; Ryan et
al., 2008) shift over time into intrinsic (self-driven) or moral goals?
Understanding how successful strategies and motivations operate without
intervention will provide crucial information about how to support new
veg*ns in a long-term change with intervention.
</p>
