<h5>
Presentation 2: An investigation of moral emotion and moral belief in
dietary choice: Exploring the attitudes of different dietary groups and
genders and their experience of guilt and disgust.
</h5>

<p>
Authors: Maria Ioannidou, Kathryn Francis, Valerie Lesk, &amp; Barbara
Stewart-Knox<br>
Speaker: Maria Ioannidou (University of Bradford)
</p>

<h5>Abstract
</h5>

<p>
Previous studies have focused on disgust and meat consumption in
vegans, vegetarians and omnivores with the finding that vegans and
vegetarians experience more disgust than omnivores. The present study
extended this and investigated how dietary groups experience the moral
emotions of disgust and guilt as well as looking at their attitudes towards
animals. Gender differences were also investigated. Participants (N =
554) were omnivores, vegetarians, pescatarians and vegans and were
recruited online. They were randomly presented with measures of disgust,
guilt, attitudes towards animals and carnistic beliefs. Measures were
adapted to include items for dairy, eggs and fish products. The results
indicated that the dietary groups differed significantly in all measures.
These differences were also found between genders, replicating previous
findings in the field. This study provides a broader understanding into how
guilt and disgust are experienced in terms of dairy, eggs and fish in these
four dietary groups.
</p>
