<h5>Presentation 3: A social identity model of vegan advocacy
</h5>
<p>
Authors: 
Madeline Judge, Julian Fernando, &amp; Christopher Begeny <br>
Speaker: Madeline Judge (University of Groningen)</p>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
In most previous research, veganism has been conceptualized as an
individual dietary behaviour. However, vegans may also consider
themselves members of a social movement acting on behalf on non-human
animals, and may consequently be motivated to engage in everyday
advocacy with the goal of encouraging social change. We develop and test
a social identity model of vegan advocacy, drawing on existing literature on
the role of social identities, emotions and efficacy in collective action. In a
sample of self-identified vegans from Australia and the UK (N = 351), moral
convictions predicted higher willingness to engage in vegan advocacy, both
directly and indirectly via the more proximal predictors of vegan
identification, group efficacy and anger. In a subset of this study, we
explored the correlations between different construals of the human-animal
relationship, emotions, and solidarity with non-human animals. Implications
for understanding processes of social change in this context will be
discussed.
</p>
